        analyze:    "A wound biopsy taken at day 7 post-injury shows: abundant neutrophils and macrophages, no fibroblasts, minimal new collagen deposition, no new capillary formation, and no keratinocyte migration at the wound edge. Analyse: (a) identify which phase the wound should have entered by day 7; (b) determine which cell type is failing to arrive or function; (c) propose two systemic conditions that could account for failure of the proliferation phase to begin; (d) predict the consequence at day 21 if the impairment is not corrected.",
        evaluate:   "A nurse proposes applying a dry, non-adherent dressing to a partial-thickness burn wound, reasoning that 'a dry environment will prevent bacteria from growing in the wound.' Evaluate this clinical decision against the biology of wound healing. Address: (a) the effect of desiccation on keratinocyte migration during re-epithelialisation; (b) the effect on granulation tissue formation; (c) the actual evidence base for moist wound healing; (d) what dressing type is indicated and why.",
        create:     "Construct a wound management plan for a 70-year-old patient on long-term oral prednisolone (corticosteroid) for rheumatoid arthritis, presenting with a 4 cm surgical wound at day 10 that has not closed — the wound base shows pale, sparse granulation tissue and no epithelial migration from the wound edge. Your plan must: (a) identify which wound healing phases are impaired by corticosteroids and the cellular mechanism; (b) recommend a specific dressing type for each healing phase with biological justification; (c) propose two systemic interventions to support healing; (d) define a measurable milestone at day 21 and state your management if it is not met."
