        remember:   "List the four major receptor classes. For each, state: its location in the cell, the chemical nature of its typical ligand (hydrophilic or hydrophobic), the speed of the response it mediates, and one specific example receptor with its ligand.",
        understand: "Explain why ligand-gated ion channels produce cellular responses within milliseconds while intracellular receptors produce responses over hours to days. Your answer must identify the number and type of molecular events between ligand binding and cellular response in each case, and connect response speed to the physiological context in which each receptor type is used.",
        apply:      "A patient has a homozygous loss-of-function mutation in the kinase domain of the insulin receptor. Predict the effect on each of the following, and explain the mechanism at each step: (a) insulin binding to the receptor; (b) receptor autophosphorylation; (c) IRS-1 recruitment and phosphorylation; (d) PI3K/Akt activation; (e) GLUT4 surface expression; (f) fasting and postprandial blood glucose levels.",
        analyze:    "Cell type A responds to ligand X with a response within 2 milliseconds that involves a change in membrane potential. Cell type B responds to ligand X with a transcriptional response that peaks at 6 hours. Cell type C responds to ligand X with cAMP elevation within 30 seconds. Analyse what receptor type each cell type is most likely expressing, justify using response speed and mechanism, and predict one specific intracellular event that would differ between each cell type.",
        evaluate:   "Evaluate the following experimental claim: 'We confirmed that our drug acts via a GPCR because adding pertussis toxin (which ADP-ribosylates and inactivates Gα-i) blocked the drug's effect on adenylyl cyclase.' Identify the error in this reasoning, explain which G protein subtype pertussis toxin acts on and what its effect on adenylyl cyclase activity would be, and propose what the correct experimental result should look like if the drug genuinely acts via a Gi-coupled GPCR.",
